Writing the ADR first, then the package.  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-gpt54/docs/adr/ADR-001-rate-limiter-design.md', content='# ADR-001: Distributed rate limiter design\n\n## Status\nAccepted\n\n## Date\n2026-04-23\n\n## Problem statement and scope\n\nWe need a standalone Python package that exposes reusable rate limiting primitives for application code, decorators, and ASGI middleware. The package must support local single-process testing and distributed deployments backed by Redis. It must return structured admission decisions with retry timing metadata and must remain correct under concurrent access, including lost-update races.\n\nThis ADR covers:\n\n- supported limiting algorithms;\n- backend abstraction and concurrency model;\n- time source and clock-skew policy;\n- API surface needed by decorators and middleware.\n\nIt does not cover multi-region replication, quota billing, adaptive rate limits, or persistent audit history.\n\n## Decision summary\n\nWe will implement:\n\n- a shared `RateLimiter` abstract base class with `enforce(key, cost=1) -> Decision`;\n- `TokenBucketLimiter` for smooth refill-based control;\n- `SlidingWindowLimiter` implemented as a sliding-window counter;\n- a `Backend` protocol with `InMemoryBackend` and `RedisBackend`;\n- `RedisBackend` using Lua scripts for atomic read-modify-write operations;\n- middleware and decorator adapters layered on top of the common limiter API.\n\n## Token bucket vs sliding window\n\n### Token bucket\n\nToken bucket works best when short bursts should be tolerated while long-term throughput remains bounded. It models a bucket that refills continuously up to a capacity. Clients may spend accumulated credit in a burst and then are throttled until refill catches up.\n\nAdvantages:\n\n- smooth average rate control;\n- burst tolerance is explicit via capacity;\n- efficient state footprint: one balance and one timestamp per key.\n\nDisadvantages:\n\n- not ideal when policy language is expressed as “no more than N requests in the last T seconds”;\n- remaining capacity is an approximation of budget, not an exact count over a fixed trailing window.\n\n### Sliding window\n\nSliding window is better when operators want hard enforcement over a trailing interval, e.g. “100 requests per 60 seconds”. It provides intuitively fair behavior near window boundaries and avoids the fixed-window double-burst problem.\n\nAdvantages:\n\n- closer match to common product quotas;\n- fairer at window edges than fixed windows;\n- reset timing can be expressed directly from the current and previous buckets.\n\nDisadvantages:\n\n- more bookkeeping than token bucket;\n- counter variant is approximate within a bucket, while log variant has higher storage and cleanup cost.\n\n## Sliding-window-log vs sliding-window-counter\n\nWe choose **sliding-window counter** rather than sliding-window log.\n\nWhy:\n\n- bounded state per key: current bucket count, previous bucket count, and current bucket start;\n- predictable Redis memory usage;\n- simpler atomic update logic than storing and pruning timestamp logs;\n- better fit for high-cardinality keys.\n\nTradeoffs named explicitly:\n\n- The counter is an approximation because all events in a sub-window bucket are treated as uniformly distributed. This can slightly under- or over-estimate exact trailing usage near bucket edges.\n- A log is exact for the trailing interval but requires storing many timestamps, pruning old entries, and handling higher write amplification.\n\nFor this package, bounded resource usage and operational simplicity are more important than exact per-request history.\n\n## Redis concurrency model: Lua vs WATCH/MULTI/EXEC\n\nWe choose **Lua scripts** for Redis operations.\n\nWhy:\n\n- atomic read-modify-write in a single round trip;\n- no client-side retry loop under contention;\n- straightforward protection against lost-update races;\n- the script can use Redis server time (`TIME`) as the source of truth, reducing cross-node clock skew.\n\n`WATCH`/`MULTI`/`EXEC` was rejected because it pushes retry logic into the client, creates more network round trips, and becomes noisy under high contention. It can be made correct, but Lua is simpler and more deterministic for this workload.\n\n## Clock-skew policy for distributed deployments\n\nPolicy:\n\n- Redis-backed decisions use **Redis server time** as authoritative time.\n- In-memory decisions use the local monotonic clock for refill and a wall clock only when producing `reset_ts`.\n- Consumers must treat `reset_ts` and `retry_after_ms` as advisory metadata derived from the backend authority in use.\n\nRationale:\n\n- distributed clients can disagree on local wall clocks;\n- relying on Redis time keeps all workers evaluating the same key against a shared clock domain;\n- monotonic local time avoids issues from local wall-clock jumps in single-process mode.\n\nConsequence:\n\n- when falling back from Redis to local mode, exact timing semantics may shift, but correctness within the chosen authority is preserved.\n\n## Rejected alternatives\n\n### 1. Fixed-window counters\n\nRejected because they allow boundary double bursts: a client can consume the full limit just before the window ends and immediately consume it again after rollover. That behavior is often surprising and too permissive.\n\n### 2. Sliding-window log\n\nRejected for the primary implementation because exactness comes with unbounded per-key event storage, higher pruning cost, and more expensive Redis operations. For a library meant to be safe under concurrency and high cardinality, that operational cost is not justified.\n\n### 3. Redis WATCH/MULTI/EXEC transactions\n\nRejected as the default Redis mechanism because correctness requires retry loops under contention, increasing latency and implementation complexity. Lua achieves the same atomicity in one server-side unit.\n\n### 4. Pure application-node clocks for Redis decisions\n\nRejected because independently skewed clocks across workers would create inconsistent admission decisions and retry calculations for the same key.\n\n## Consequences\n\nPositive:\n\n- uniform limiter API across algorithms and backends;\n- bounded memory usage for both algorithms;\n- atomic distributed correctness with Redis;\n- middleware and decorators stay thin because the decision model is shared.\n\nNegative:\n\n- sliding-window counter is approximate rather than exact;\n- Redis backend depends on script support;\n- reset timestamps from local and Redis modes may differ slightly because they use different authorities.\n\n## Implementation notes\n\n- `Decision.remaining` is clamped at zero.\n- `retry_after_ms` is zero when a request is allowed.\n- `cost` must be positive.\n- public surface must not expose placeholders or `NotImplementedError`.\n')
