  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-gpt54/docs/design.md', content='# Design\n\nThis package provides a reusable rate-limiting core with two algorithms, two storage backends, a decorator adapter, and ASGI middleware for FastAPI or Starlette. The implementation is intentionally small, but it is structured so that application code uses a single `enforce()` interface regardless of whether the limiter is running in-process or against Redis.\n\n## Overview\n\nThe request path is the same for middleware, decorators, and direct library calls:\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n    A[Incoming request or function call] --> B[Key extraction]\n    B --> C[Limiter enforce(key, cost)]\n    C --> D[Algorithm-specific backend operation]\n    D --> E[Decision]\n    E --> F[Allow and attach headers]\n    E --> G[Deny and emit retry metadata]\n```\n\nThe middleware layer turns transport-specific input into a key, delegates enforcement to a limiter, and maps the returned `Decision` into HTTP headers and a `429` response when needed. The decorator does the same mapping for Python callables by raising a typed exception.\n\n## Components\n\n### `Decision`\n\n`Decision` is the normalized output of all enforcement calls:\n\n- `allowed`: whether the request may proceed;\n- `retry_after_ms`: how long until retry is likely to succeed;\n- `remaining`: estimated remaining capacity after the decision;\n- `reset_ts`: epoch milliseconds when the limiter is expected to be fully reset or fully replenished.\n\nA common decision object keeps middleware and decorators algorithm-agnostic.\n\n### Algorithms\n\n#### Token bucket\n\nToken bucket stores a token balance and the last refill timestamp for each key. Every call first refills based on elapsed time, clamps the balance to capacity, and then attempts to spend `cost`. This algorithm is a good default for APIs that want to allow bursts while still constraining average rate.\n\nThe implementation uses floating-point token balances so fractional refill between calls is preserved. `retry_after_ms` is based on the deficit divided by refill rate.\n\n#### Sliding-window counter\n\nSliding-window counter tracks three values per key: current bucket start, current bucket count, and previous bucket count. Effective usage is computed as:\n\n```text\ncurrent_count + previous_count * overlap_weight\n```\n\nwhere `overlap_weight` shrinks linearly as the current period advances. This approximates a true sliding-window log but keeps state bounded and cheap to update.\n\nThe chosen semantics are stronger than fixed windows at bucket boundaries and operationally cheaper than logs in Redis.\n\n## Backends\n\n### In-memory backend\n\n`InMemoryBackend` is used for single-process deployments and tests. It stores key state in Python dictionaries protected by a re-entrant lock. The lock makes compound read-modify-write operations atomic within one process and is sufficient for thread-based concurrency tests. It does not coordinate across processes.\n\nTime handling is split deliberately:\n\n- `time.monotonic()` drives token refill math, protecting against local wall-clock jumps;\n- wall-clock time is used only to produce `reset_ts` values for callers.\n\n### Redis backend\n\n`RedisBackend` is the distributed option. Each algorithm is implemented as a Lua script loaded into Redis. The script performs the entire enforcement flow atomically:\n\n1. read current state for the key;\n2. obtain authoritative server time with `TIME`;\n3. compute refill or sliding-window overlap;\n4. decide allow/deny;\n5. write back updated state and TTL;\n6. return decision fields.\n\nThis design prevents lost updates because no two clients can interleave the read and write portions of the same key mutation.\n\nUsing Redis server time also gives a single clock domain for all application workers. That matters for `retry_after_ms` and `reset_ts`, especially when hosts have imperfect NTP sync.\n\n## Request flow through middleware\n\n```text\nHTTP request\n  -> key_fn(request)\n  -> limiter.enforce(key)\n  -> backend atomic state transition\n  -> Decision\n     -> allowed: forward request, attach X-RateLimit-* headers\n     -> denied: return 429, attach X-RateLimit-* and Retry-After\n```\n\nHeaders emitted:\n\n- `X-RateLimit-Limit`\n- `X-RateLimit-Remaining`\n- `X-RateLimit-Reset`\n- `Retry-After` on denial\n\nThe middleware stays thin on purpose. All policy is pushed into the limiter and backend so behavior stays consistent across direct calls, decorators, and HTTP traffic.\n\n## Failure modes\n\n### Redis unavailable\n\nIf Redis cannot be reached, the backend will raise. The middleware supports a configurable degradation strategy through `fail_open`:\n\n- `fail_open=True` allows the request through without headers when the limiter infrastructure is unavailable;\n- `fail_open=False` propagates the backend failure so the application can fail closed.\n\nFail-open is a pragmatic default for user-facing systems where availability matters more than temporary quota enforcement. Fail-closed is appropriate for sensitive endpoints or expensive downstream operations.\n\n### Script cache miss\n\nRedis may forget a previously loaded script after restart or failover. The backend detects `NOSCRIPT`, reloads scripts, and retries transparently.\n\n### Local process restarts\n\nIn-memory state disappears on restart. That is acceptable because the backend is explicitly scoped to tests and single-process usage.\n\n### Approximation error in sliding window\n\nThe sliding-window counter is not exact. Near bucket boundaries, effective usage is an approximation. The tradeoff is accepted because memory and CPU remain bounded while boundary fairness remains much better than fixed-window counters.\n\n## Degradation strategy\n\nThe system is designed so transport adapters do not need special-case logic for algorithm details. When Redis is reachable, the distributed backend provides correct cross-worker enforcement. When Redis is unavailable, applications should choose policy explicitly:\n\n- use `InMemoryBackend` in tests, local development, or intentionally single-process services;\n- use `RedisBackend` in distributed production;\n- configure middleware to fail open or fail closed based on endpoint criticality.\n\nThis keeps the package predictable: correctness is strongest when Redis is present, but operational behavior under backend failure is still under application control.\n')
  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-gpt54/README.md', content='# ratelimit\n\nDistributed rate limiter with token-bucket and sliding-window algorithms, in-memory and Redis backends, a decorator, and Starlette/FastAPI middleware.\n\n## Install\n\n```bash\npip install -e .\n```\n\n## Features\n\n- `TokenBucketLimiter` for burst-tolerant rate control\n- `SlidingWindowLimiter` for trailing-window style limits\n- `InMemoryBackend` for tests and single-process use\n- `RedisBackend` using atomic Lua scripts\n- `@rate_limit(...)` decorator for sync and async functions\n- `RateLimitMiddleware` for ASGI apps\n\n## Token bucket example\n\n```python\nfrom ratelimit import InMemoryBackend, TokenBucketLimiter\n\nbackend = InMemoryBackend()\nlimiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=backend, capacity=10, refill_rate=5)\n\ndecision = limiter.enforce("user:123")\nif decision.allowed:\n    print("ok", decision.remaining)\nelse:\n    print("retry in ms", decision.retry_after_ms)\n```\n\n## Sliding window example\n\n```python\nfrom ratelimit import InMemoryBackend, SlidingWindowLimiter\n\nbackend = InMemoryBackend()\nlimiter = SlidingWindowLimiter(backend=backend, limit=100, period_ms=60_000)\n\nfor _ in range(3):\n    print(limiter.enforce("ip:127.0.0.1"))\n```\n\n## Decorator example\n\n```python\nfrom ratelimit import InMemoryBackend, RateLimitExceeded, TokenBucketLimiter, rate_limit\n\nbackend = InMemoryBackend()\nlimiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=backend, capacity=2, refill_rate=1)\n\n@rate_limit(limiter, key_fn=lambda user_id: f"user:{user_id}")\ndef greet(user_id: str) -> str:\n    return f"hello {user_id}"\n\ntry:\n    greet("42")\nexcept RateLimitExceeded as exc:\n    print(exc.decision.retry_after_ms)\n```\n\n## Middleware example\n\n```python\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI, Request\nfrom ratelimit import InMemoryBackend, RateLimitMiddleware, SlidingWindowLimiter\n\napp = FastAPI()\nlimiter = SlidingWindowLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), limit=20, period_ms=60_000)\napp.add_middleware(RateLimitMiddleware, limiter=limiter, key_fn=lambda request: request.client.host)\n\n@app.get("/")\nasync def index(request: Request):\n    return {"ok": True}\n```\n\nDenied responses include:\n\n- `X-RateLimit-Limit`\n- `X-RateLimit-Remaining`\n- `X-RateLimit-Reset`\n- `Retry-After`\n\n## Redis backend example\n\n```python\nfrom redis import Redis\nfrom ratelimit import RedisBackend, TokenBucketLimiter\n\nclient = Redis.from_url("redis://localhost:6379/0")\nbackend = RedisBackend(client)\nlimiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=backend, capacity=50, refill_rate=10)\n\nprint(limiter.enforce("tenant:abc"))\n```\n\n## Operational caveats\n\n- `InMemoryBackend` is process-local and not safe for multi-process distributed enforcement.\n- `RedisBackend` uses Redis server time as the timing authority; this avoids worker clock skew.\n- Sliding-window enforcement uses a counter approximation, not an exact request log.\n- Middleware can be configured fail-open when Redis is unavailable; choose this deliberately.\n\n## Development\n\n```bash\npytest\n```\n\nSee `docs/adr/ADR-001-rate-limiter-design.md` and `docs/design.md` for design details.\n')
  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-2-ratelimit/worktrees/duh-gpt54/tests/test_ratelimit.py', content='from __future__ import annotations\n\nimport threading\nimport time\n\nimport fakeredis\nimport pytest\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI\nfrom fastapi.testclient import TestClient\nfrom hypothesis import given, settings\nfrom hypothesis import strategies as st\n\nfrom ratelimit import (\n    InMemoryBackend,\n    RateLimitExceeded,\n    RateLimitMiddleware,\n    RedisBackend,\n    SlidingWindowLimiter,\n    TokenBucketLimiter,\n    rate_limit,\n)\n\n\nclass TestTokenBucketLimiter:\n    def test_allows_until_capacity(self) -> None:\n        limiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), capacity=3, refill_rate=10)\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is True\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is True\n        third = limiter.enforce("a")\n        assert third.allowed is True\n        blocked = limiter.enforce("a")\n        assert blocked.allowed is False\n        assert blocked.retry_after_ms > 0\n        assert blocked.remaining == 0\n\n    def test_refills_over_time(self) -> None:\n        limiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), capacity=1, refill_rate=20)\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is True\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is False\n        time.sleep(0.06)\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is True\n\n    def test_cost_must_be_positive(self) -> None:\n        limiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), capacity=1, refill_rate=1)\n        with pytest.raises(ValueError):\n            limiter.enforce("a", cost=0)\n\n\nclass TestSlidingWindowLimiter:\n    def test_blocks_after_limit(self) -> None:\n        limiter = SlidingWindowLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), limit=2, period_ms=1000)\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is True\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is True\n        denied = limiter.enforce("a")\n        assert denied.allowed is False\n        assert denied.retry_after_ms > 0\n\n    def test_isolates_keys(self) -> None:\n        limiter = SlidingWindowLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), limit=1, period_ms=1000)\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is True\n        assert limiter.enforce("b").allowed is True\n\n    def test_capacity_one_edge(self) -> None:\n        limiter = SlidingWindowLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), limit=1, period_ms=100)\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is True\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is False\n\n\nclass TestDecorator:\n    def test_sync_decorator(self) -> None:\n        limiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), capacity=1, refill_rate=100)\n\n        @rate_limit(limiter, key_fn=lambda user: user)\n        def fn(user: str) -> str:\n            return user\n\n        assert fn("u") == "u"\n        with pytest.raises(RateLimitExceeded):\n            fn("u")\n\n    @pytest.mark.asyncio\n    async def test_async_decorator_reentry(self) -> None:\n        limiter = SlidingWindowLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), limit=2, period_ms=1000)\n\n        @rate_limit(limiter, key_fn=lambda user: user)\n        async def fn(user: str) -> str:\n            return user\n\n        assert await fn("u") == "u"\n        assert await fn("u") == "u"\n        with pytest.raises(RateLimitExceeded):\n            await fn("u")\n\n\nclass TestMiddleware:\n    def test_adds_headers_and_blocks(self) -> None:\n        app = FastAPI()\n        limiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), capacity=1, refill_rate=1)\n        app.add_middleware(RateLimitMiddleware, limiter=limiter, key_fn=lambda request: "client")\n\n        @app.get("/")\n        def index() -> dict[str, bool]:\n            return {"ok": True}\n\n        client = TestClient(app)\n        allowed = client.get("/")\n        assert allowed.status_code == 200\n        assert allowed.headers["X-RateLimit-Limit"] == "1"\n        blocked = client.get("/")\n        assert blocked.status_code == 429\n        assert blocked.headers["Retry-After"] == "1"\n\n    def test_fail_open(self) -> None:\n        class BrokenLimiter:\n            capacity = 1\n\n            def enforce(self, key: str, cost: int = 1):\n                raise RuntimeError("down")\n\n        app = FastAPI()\n        app.add_middleware(RateLimitMiddleware, limiter=BrokenLimiter(), key_fn=lambda request: "k", fail_open=True)\n\n        @app.get("/")\n        def index() -> dict[str, bool]:\n            return {"ok": True}\n\n        client = TestClient(app)\n        response = client.get("/")\n        assert response.status_code == 200\n\n\nclass TestRedisBackend:\n    def test_fakeredis_integration(self) -> None:\n        client = fakeredis.FakeRedis()\n        backend = RedisBackend(client)\n        limiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=backend, capacity=2, refill_rate=100)\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is True\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is True\n        assert limiter.enforce("a").allowed is False\n\n\ndef test_inmemory_token_bucket_concurrency() -> None:\n    limiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), capacity=20, refill_rate=0.0001)\n    allowed = 0\n    lock = threading.Lock()\n    barrier = threading.Barrier(120)\n\n    def worker() -> None:\n        nonlocal allowed\n        barrier.wait()\n        decision = limiter.enforce("shared")\n        if decision.allowed:\n            with lock:\n                allowed += 1\n\n    threads = [threading.Thread(target=worker) for _ in range(120)]\n    for thread in threads:\n        thread.start()\n    for thread in threads:\n        thread.join()\n\n    assert allowed == 20\n\n\ndef test_redis_token_bucket_concurrency() -> None:\n    client = fakeredis.FakeRedis()\n    limiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=RedisBackend(client), capacity=15, refill_rate=0.0001)\n    allowed = 0\n    lock = threading.Lock()\n    barrier = threading.Barrier(100)\n\n    def worker() -> None:\n        nonlocal allowed\n        barrier.wait()\n        decision = limiter.enforce("shared")\n        if decision.allowed:\n            with lock:\n                allowed += 1\n\n    threads = [threading.Thread(target=worker) for _ in range(100)]\n    for thread in threads:\n        thread.start()\n    for thread in threads:\n        thread.join()\n\n    assert allowed == 15\n\n\n@given(st.lists(st.integers(min_value=0, max_value=10), min_size=1, max_size=30))\n@settings(max_examples=50)\ndef test_token_bucket_property_never_exceeds_capacity(offsets: list[int]) -> None:\n    capacity = 5\n    refill_rate = 1000.0 / 1000.0\n    limiter = TokenBucketLimiter(backend=InMemoryBackend(), capacity=capacity, refill_rate=refill_rate)\n    start = time.time()\n    granted_times: list[float] = []\n\n    for offset in offsets:\n        target = start + (offset / 1000.0)\n        while time.time() < target:\n            time.sleep(0.0005)\n        decision = limiter.enforce("prop")\n        if decision.allowed:\n            granted_times.append(time.time())\n\n    period = capacity / refill_rate\n    for current in granted_times:\n        in_window = [t for t in granted_times if current - period <= t <= current]\n        assert len(in_window) <= capacity\n')
